==English==

===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|la|igneus|t=fiery}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈɪɡni.əs/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-igneous.wav|Audio (RP)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# Pertaining to or having the nature of fire; containing fire; resembling fire.
#: {{ux|en|The stone had an '''igneous''' appearance.}}
# {{lb|en|geology}} Resulting from, or produced by, great heat. With rocks, it could also mean formed from [[lava]] or [[magma]].
#: {{ux|en|Granite and basalt are '''igneous''' rocks.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Charles Lyell|authorlink=Charles Lyell|title=Principles of Geology|year=1833|volume=III|section=book IV|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/principlesgeolo27lyelgoog/page/n391/mode/1up|page=385|passage=All formations, whether '''igneous''' or aqueous, which can be shown by any such proofs to be of a date posterior to the introduction of man, will be called ''Recent''.}}

